{"ticker": "FIGURE_AI_INC", "company": "Figure AI Inc.", "weight_sum": 9.81, "etfs": ["ARKSX", "ARKUX", "ARKVX"], "is_private": true, "query": "\"Figure AI\" -is:retweet min_faves:10 since_time:1777826744 until_time:1777834745", "n_fetched": 1, "n_kept": 1, "n_dropped": 0, "kept": [{"type": "tweet", "id": "2050994765236515011", "url": "https://x.com/lev_eth/status/2050994765236515011", "twitterUrl": "https://twitter.com/lev_eth/status/2050994765236515011", "text": "Looked at where humanoid robotics actually stands right now and it is splitting into two completely different games.\n\nFigure AI just closed Series C at $39B valuation. 1X opened a US factory last week targeting 100K robots by 2027. Tesla is converting the Fremont Model S/X line to build Optimus. These three are racing for the general purpose market of homes, warehouses, and factories, backed by billions in equity and Big Tech capital.\n\n@StrikeRobot_ai is playing a completely different game. Specialist deployment in nuclear facilities, high voltage zones, and chemical plants. Environments where general purpose humanoids are not allowed today and where the unit economics work because the alternative is putting humans at risk.\n\nThere is also a structural piece that none of the others have. Figure and 1X will sell or lease robots through traditional B2B contracts. $SR is building a Physical AI BPO model where the robot itself becomes the economic agent, paid in stablecoins through ERC-8004 and x402, with revenue flowing back to token holders directly.\n\nThe general purpose race already costs $39B to enter. The specialist on-chain race is still early enough that the market has not figured out how to price it yet.", "source": "Twitter for iPhone", "retweetCount": 0, "replyCount": 9, "likeCount": 14, "quoteCount": 0, "viewCount": 113, "createdAt": "Sun May 03 17:43:52 +0000 2026", "lang": "en", "bookmarkCount": 2, "isReply": false, "inReplyToId": null, "conversationId": "2050994765236515011", "displayText